&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span></span><![endif]><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>Colonies wi=
th
Wonders<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>You can find unused s=
cenic
locations in the &#8220;Potential Resort Locations&#8221; list in the Empire
Navigation Tool. You can also find scenic locations by using the Galaxy Map=
 (G
key), selecting the &#8220;Scenic Locations&#8221; filter.<o:p></o:p></span=
></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>Colonies with ancient=
 ruins
or wonders will attract tourism without the need to build a resort base at =
the
colony.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>The volume of tourist=
s that a
resort attracts depends on how scenic the location is, and how close it is =
to
large, wealthy colonies. The wealthy citizens of these kinds of colonies ar=
e on
the lookout for scenic tourism destinations to travel to.<o:p></o:p></span>=
</p>

<h3><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>Income from Tourism<o:p></o:p></span><=
/h3>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>Income is derived when
passenger ships arrive at a resort. The amount of income depends on how many
passengers the ship was carrying. This variable income is shown in the Econ=
omy
summary on the Empire Summary screen (F6).<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'mso-no-proof:yes'>Tourism also occurs a=
cross
empire boundaries (as long as relations between two empires are not war or
trade sanctions). So passenger ships can transport visitors from the colony=
 of
one empire to the Resort Base of another empire.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

